[1]
Date: Wed 8 Sep 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Channel NewsAsia, 8 Sep 2004 [edited]
<http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/southeastasia/view/105582/1/.html>


2 cleared of bird flu in Malaysia as efforts intensify to contain outbreak
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Malaysia heaved a sigh of relief, as 2 people under observation for
possible bird flu infection have been cleared of the disease. (For
background on the patients see below. [3])

Malaysia's Health Minister, Chua Soi Lek, pledged that
round-the-clock 24-hour surveillance would continue until the
affected areas are declared free from the H5 N1 virus. Speaking after
the weekly cabinet meeting, he announced that a veterinary worker,
suspected of having bird flu, has been diagnosed as suffering from
acute gastroenteritis instead. The 45-year-old woman, who was
involved in the testing of samples for the bird flu virus, had a
fever and diarrhea.

As for the 10-year-old boy admitted for suspected bird flu, he is now
out of [danger]. The boy had a fever and cough. Mr. Chua said: "His
X-ray is normal. We don't think this is a case of avian flu; we just
want to be more cautious, that's all. Active surveillance is ongoing;
we have inspected 340 houses."

The new outbreak of bird flu, which has killed 27 people across Asia
this year [2004], was found in Belian village, near Pasir Pekan, in
Kelantan, where the 1st outbreak occurred last month [August 2004].
Although there is no case of human infection, the health authorities
are conducting door to door checks around the clock, within the 1km
radius of the affected village, to keep the deadly disease
at bay. More than 2500 people have been screened, and nearly 1400
birds, including chickens, ducks, and pet birds, have been culled.

The authorities believe that the 10 chickens and 20 quail that died
could have eaten the contaminated leftovers of birds smuggled in from
across the border with Thailand. This has prompted the government to
tighten controls at all border checkpoints and to place immediate
restrictions on the movement of birds within a 10 kilometer radius of
the affected areas.

Malaysia's Veterinary Services Department is now in discussion with
Singapore's Agri Food and Veterinary Authorities on allowing poultry
and eggs from selected farms to be imported into Singapore. Kerk Choo
Teng, Malaysian Deputy Minister, Agriculture and Agro-based Industry
Ministry, said: "Singapore requires quite a high standard of safety.
Most of the farms...comply with this high standard of requirement."

Malaysia exports nearly half its poultry, and a third of its eggs, to
Singapore and hopes the island republic will resume imports from
farms in the southern states of Johor and Malacca. A total ban by
Singapore, Japan, and Taiwan, since mid-August 2004, has threatened
the country's 6-billion ringgit [USD 1 579 000 000] poultry industry.

[Byline: Melissa Goh]

