[2]
Date: Wed 8 Sep 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Star online, Malaysia, 8 Sep 2004 [edited]
<http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2004/9/8/nation/8847626&sec=nation>


900 chickens, ducks, and birds culled in Kelantan
-------------------------------------------------
Almost 900 chickens, ducks, and birds have been culled, following the
detection of new avian flu cases in Kampung Belian on Sunday [5 Sep
2004]. The village is about 5km from Kampung Pasir Pekan, in
Kelantan, where the virus was 1st detected on 17 Aug 2004.

Veterinary Services Department director-general Datuk Dr. Hawari
Hussein said that the culling activities began on Monday [6 Sep 2004]
night in Kampung Belian, and within a 1km radius of the
area, after 30 chickens and quails, belonging to a villager in
Kampung Belianhad, died from Highly Pathogenic Avian Influenza (HPAI).

A veterinary department worker, a 10-year-old boy, and a teenage girl
from Kampung Belian have been hospitalized for observation, as they
had avian flu-like symptoms, including fever and coughing. [The first 2 have
been excluded as cases -- see above. - Mod.JW]

"As of Tuesday [7 Sep 2004] morning, a total of 888, out of 1200
chickens, ducks, and birds, have been culled. Culling activities are
ongoing for the remaining 300. We can only start the 21-day
disease-free countdown for the area once culling activities have been
completed," he said in a statement yesterday [Tue 7 Sep 2004].

The earlier quarantine, imposed on a 10km radius around Kampung Pasir
Pekan, that includes Kampung Belian, was to have ended tomorrow [Thu
9 Sep 2004]. Although there have been no further cases of HPAI, Dr.
Hawari said that frequent inspections, monitoring, and surveillance
activities would continue within the quarantine areas, and throughout
the country, as a precautionary measure. "No new signs of HPAI have
been detected, and locations outside the 10km quarantine area are
free from the disease," he said, adding that eggs, chickens, and
ducks in the market were still safe for consumption.

Dr. Hawari advised the public, especially those living near the Thai
border, to cooperate with authorities and not bring any poultry, or
related products, into the country. "Poultry and related products
from Thailand are still barred from being brought into the country,"
he added.

